@NODE "Introduction"

  Prime
  -----

  This short program calculates all primenumbers till a given maximum.
You can save all found primenumbers to a file.

  Prime uses the "Sieve of Eratosthenes", and requires a processor >= 68020.
It uses special optimizations for 68040- and 68060-processors.

Since version 6 you can test 64-bit-integers. This enlarges the possible
range from 4e9 up to 1e19 (10,000,000,000,000,000,000 !). Now Prime can
tell you all dividers of a given number.

        @{"Next" LINK Usage}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage"

@{b}Usage@{ub}
-----

  Prime can only be called from the shell.
Argument-template:  Prime MAX/A,FILE/K,BIGBUFFER=BB/S,
                          RANGESTART=RS/N,RANGEEND=RE/N,
                          TEST/S,RECURSIVE=R/S,PROCESSOR=P/N

Meaning of the options:
 MAX        - maximum number for the search
 FILE       - file, the numbers are written in
 BIGBUFFER  - if you use this option, a bigger outputbuffer will be used
              without BB: 8 KByte, with BB: 256 KByte
 RANGESTART - startnumber for output
 RANGEEND   - end of range for output
 TEST       - test value of MAX
 RECURSIVE  - find all factors of MAX
 PROCESSOR  - switch processor dependent code

  Prime can be interrupted with CTRL-C if it is in the output-loop. If
you dont supply a filename, no primenumbers will be written. If the RANGE-
parameters aren't correct, they will be internally replaced by default
values, eg. 0 for RANGESTART and MAX for RANGEEND. The minimum for
MAX is 2000 due to the calculation algorithm.

  If TEST is selected, only the MAX-value is used. The program will test
MAX and output the result.

  The parameters are checked via the DOS/ReadArgs-function. This is important
for the integer-arguments RS and RE. The Operating System (OS) handles these
numbers as signed 32-bit-integers! ReadArgs (OS 3.1) accepts numbers in the
range from -2,147,483,649 till +2,147,483,649. Internally +2,147,483,649 equals
-2,147,483,647, what is represented by $8000,0001.

  The routine for calculating primenumbers accepts arguments till 2,147,483,647
(= $7fff,ffff). This would result in using a memory block of 128 MB.

  When testing numbers the maximum value depends on the PROCESSOR argument.
With the 68020/68040-optimization you can test numbers up to 10^19-1
(9,999,999,999,999,999,999). When using the 68060-optimization, only
numbers up to 2^62-1 (4,611,686,018,427,387,903) are allowed.

  Normally Prime uses the operating system to determine the processor
it runs on. But you could override this by using the PROCESSOR argu-
ment. Three values are allowed: 68020, 68040 and 68060. The 68020-
option is appropriate for 68030 too.

        @{"Next" LINK SpeedSieve}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SpeedSieve"

@{b}Speed (Sieve)@{ub}
-------------

  In version 7 the calculation of primenumbers is slightly changed. So
the timings changed a little bit too. Additionally the Forbid/Permit-
pair in the calculation routine was removed to enable the multitasking,
when Prime is running. For measuring accurate timings you have to set
the task priority to higher values (I prefer 30).

On my AMIGA (A500, 68030/50MHz, 68882/50MHz, 16/1 MB) the command
"Prime MAX .. FILE DH3:Test BB" needs the following time:

      MAX      Sieve  Count   Output  counted
                 [s]    [s]      [s]  primenumbers
   1.000.000    0.28   0.04     3.58       78498
   2.000.000    0.58   0.08     6.56      148933
   5.000.000    1.60   0.14    15.90      348513
  10.000.000    3.36   0.28    30.60      664579
  20.000.000    7.20   0.58    59.44     1270607
  50.000.000   19.34   1.46   141.38     3001134
 100.000.000   40.92   2.90              5761455
 200.000.000   86.58   5.82             11078937

  The number of primenumbers to a given maximum is roughly MAX/ln(max).
The length of the written textfile can be estimated with ~10 * number
of primenumbers.

  Prime works with VMM and uses the virtual memory. It needs MAX/16 byte
plus the output-buffer of 8 (or 256) Kbyte. Because of the heavy memory
access virtual memory slows down the calculation significantly. (This was
true for my old turboboard. With the new board (E-Matrix) I couldn't
get VMM to work. So Prime together with VMM is untested.)

        @{"Next" LINK SpeedTest}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SpeedTest"

@{b}Speed (Test)@{ub}
------------

  The test-routine can test 64-bit-integers. But the routine uses a
simple loop with divide-instructions. So you get long calculation-times
for big numbers! With my Amiga I get these timings:

        MAX                Calculation
                              [s]
       99.999.999.999.973     5.7
      100.000.000.000.031     5.7
      999.999.999.999.989    18.2
    1.000.000.000.000.037    18.2
    9.999.999.999.999.937    59.8
   10.000.000.000.000.061    59.8
   99.999.999.999.999.997   213.0
  100.000.000.000.000.003   213.0
  999.999.999.999.999.989   904.4
1.000.000.000.000.000.003   904.4

  Version 7 is now about 10% faster than version 6! Additional Prime
calculates recursively all dividers of the argument (and prints them),
if you select the "RECURSIVE"-option.

  For small numbers, the calculation time grows by a factor of 3.2 per
power of ten. For bigger numbers, the program has to use its own routine
instead of the 64/32-bit-division of the processor and so the factor grows
up to 4.

  The 68060-processor has its problems with this test as it has to emulate
the used division instructions. This has a great impact on the multitasking.
Because of that I programmed a special routine, which doesn't use these
instructions. So the multitasking can run smoothly as always, but the 68060
is slower than a 68030 (with same frequency).

        @{"Next" LINK Comparision}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Comparision"

@{b}Comparision of different computers/processors@{ub}
---------------------------------------------

  Prime now contains different code for different processors.
Therefor runtimes are dependent from the used optimization.

  Some results from different systems, compared to my Amiga:

 processor  RAM   Sieve  Count   Test   comment
 68030/50    16    1.00   1.00   1.00   my Amiga
 68060/50          1.45   3.50   0.36   Simon N. Goodwin
 WinUAE      16    0.43   0.32   0.90   PII 350MHz, Windows98
 WinUAE      16    0.22   0.18   0.50   Pentium166MMX, Windows98

        @{"Next" LINK History}
@ENDNODE

